{"parse":{"title":"nation","pageid":56025,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|nâtion|Nation}}\n==English==\n{{wp}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{enPR|nā'shən}}, {{IPA|en|/ˈneɪʃən/}}\n* {{audio|en|en-us-nation.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{rhymes|en|eɪʃən|s=2}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{ety|en|id=people|:inh|enm:nacioun<id:nation>|tree=1}}\n\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|nacioun,nacion}}, from {{der|en|fro|nacion}}, from {{der|en|la|nātiōnem}}, accusative of {{m|la|nātiō||nation}}. {{displaced|ang|þēod}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{sid|en|group of persons united by some traits}} {{lb|en|collective}} A historically constituted, stable community of people, formed based on a common [[language]], [[territory]], economic life, [[ethnicity]] and/or [[psychological]] make-up manifested in a common [[culture]].\n#: {{cot|en|q1=sometimes synonymous|people#English:_group of persons, such as a nation}}\n#: {{ux|en|The Roma are a '''nation''' without a country.}}\n#: {{collocation|en|pre-Columbian '''nations'''}}\n#* {{RQ:King James Version|Psalms|22|27|passage=All the ends of the woꝛld ſhall remember, and turne vnto the {{smallcaps|Lord}}: and all the kinreds of the '''nations''' ſhall woꝛſhip befoꝛe thee.}}\n## {{sid|en|type of informal community}} {{lb|en|by extension|informal|often|jocular}} A community united by some trait (especially an [[interest#English:_something or someone as focus of attention|interest]]) but not historically constituted.\n##: {{nearsyn|en|tribe<id:type of informal community>}}\n##: {{ux|en|the Dallas Cowboys '''nation'''}}\n##* {{quote-journal |en |date=2016-05-05 |last=Anna |first=Johansson |title=5 Marketing Tips for Reaching the DIY Generation |journal=Entrepreneur |url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/growing-a-business/5-marketing-tips-for-reaching-the-diy-generation/274868 |accessdate=2023-12-21 |passage=Did Pinterest create a culture of do-it-yourselfers, or did the DIY '''nation''' create Pinterest? The answer may not be certain, but we do know that a lot of customers love to do things on their own.}}\n# {{lb|en|international|_|legal|metonymically}} A [[sovereign]] [[state]]; {{lb|en|loosely|metonymically|proscribed}} a [[country]].\n#: {{ux|en|Though legally single '''nations''', many states comprise several distinct cultural or ethnic groups.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-06-07|author=David Simpson|volume=188|issue=26|page=36|magazine=w:The Guardian Weekly|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2013/may/18/falling-upwards-richard-holmes-review|title=Fantasy of navigation|passage=It is tempting to speculate about the incentives or compulsions that might explain why anyone would take to the skies in [the] basket [of a balloon]:&nbsp;{{...}} perhaps to muse on the irrelevance of the borders that separate '''nation''' states and keep people from understanding their shared environment.}}\n#* {{quote-av|en|author=Drachinifel|title=\nAnti-Slavery Patrols - The West Africa Squadron|date=1 December 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TiSekII0sjw|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20241129115918/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TiSekII0sjw|archivedate=29 November 2024|accessdate=4 January 2025|time=1:18|text=By the start of the 19th century, Europe was neckdeep in the Napoleonic Wars, which, at various times, amounted to the British Empire against Europe, and, at others, involved Britain subsidising various '''nations''', such as Austria and Prussia, against Napoleon.}}\n# {{lb|en|chiefly|historical}} An association of [[student]]s [[base]]d on the [[birthplace]] or [[ethnicity]] of its [[member]]s.\n#: {{syn|en|student nation}}\n#: {{ux|en|Once widespread across Europe in medieval times, '''nations''' are now largely restricted to the ancient universities of Sweden and Finland.}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A great number; a great deal.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1762|author=w:Laurence Sterne|title=w:The Life and Opinions of Tristram Shandy, Gentleman|volume=V|edition=new|location=Altenburgh|publisher=G. E. Richter|year_published=1772|page=57|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=BPnSMPA8Y2sC&pg=PA57|passage={{...}}and what a '''nation''' of herbs he had procured to mollify her humours, &c. &c.{{...}}}}\n# In North America, an Indigenous [[people#English:_group of persons, such as a nation|people]] with federal and/or state [[recognition]] as such and (often also) their federally recognized territory.<!--Not all nations have territories-->\n#: {{ux|en|The Choctaw '''Nation''' is the third-largest federally recognized tribe in the United States and the second-largest Indian reservation in area.}}\n#: {{ux|en|The term ''[[Navajo Nation|Navajo '''Nation''']]'' refers both to the people and to their territory.}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* {{qualifier|British}} Following the establishment of the Scottish and Welsh [[parliament|parliaments]], [[England]], [[Scotland]] and [[Wales]] are normally considered distinct nations. Application of the term ''nation'' to the United Kingdom as a whole is [[deprecate]]d in most style guides, including the BBC, most newspapers and in UK Government publications. [[Northern Ireland]], being of less clear legal status, generally remains a [[province]].\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|egonation|nanonation|ronation\n|aspirant nation\n|bedroom nation\n|bug nation\n|captive nation\n|cybernation\n|domestic dependent nation\n|father of the nation\n|First Nation,First Nations\n|Ford Nation\n|Holy Roman Empire of the German Nation\n|home nation\n|independent mini-nation\n|indispensable nation\n|internation\n|macronation\n|micronation|Delaware Nation|Munsee-Delaware Nation\n|mini-nation\n|model nation\n|most favored nation\n|most favoured nation\n|mother of the nation\n|multination\n|natiolect\n|national\n|nation-builder\n|nation-building\n|nationful\n|nationhood\n|nationism\n|nationist\n|nationless\n|nationlike\n|Nation of Islam\n|nation of laws\n|nationship\n|nation-state\n|nation state\n|nationwide\n|nation wrecker\n|Navajo Nation\n|Neutral Nation\n|new nation project\n|one nation\n|one-nation conservatism\n|one-nation conservative\n|plurination\n|project nation\n|proposition nation\n|pseudo-nation\n|pseudonation\n|Six Nations of the Grand River\n|space nation\n|State of the Nation\n|student nation\n|subnation\n|supernation\n|Test nation\n|the race that stops a nation\n|United Nations\n}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n{{col3|en\n|antenatal\n|innate\n|nascent\n|natal\n|native\n|nativism\n|nativity\n|nativization\n|natural\n|naturalism\n|nature\n|naturism\n|prenatal\n}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|community of people}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t+|af|nasie}}, {{t+|af|volk}}\n* Albanian: {{t+|sq|komb|m}}\n* Altai:\n*: Southern Altai: {{t|alt|эл}}, {{t|alt|калык}}, {{t|alt|улус}}, {{t|alt|јурт}}, {{t|alt|аймак}}\n* Amharic: {{t|am|ብሔር}}\n* Arabic: {{t+|ar|أُمَّة|f}}, {{t|ar|قَوْم|m}}\n* Aramaic:\n*: Classical Syriac: {{t|syc|ܐܘܡܬܐ|f|tr=ʾumməṯā}}\n*: Jewish Babylonian Aramaic: {{t|arc|אוּמְּתָא|f|tr=ʾumməṯā}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|ազգ}}, {{t+|hy|ժողովուրդ}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t+|az|millət}}\n* Bashkir: {{t|ba|милләт}}\n* Belarusian: {{t+|be|на́цыя|f}}, {{t+|be|наро́д|m}}\n* Bengali: {{t+|bn|কওম}}, {{t+|bn|মিল্লত}}, {{t+|bn|উম্মত}}\n* Breton: {{t+|br|broad|m}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|на́ция|f}}, {{t+|bg|наро́д|m}}\n* Burmese: {{t|my|လူမျိုးသည်}}, {{t+|my|လူမျိုး}}, {{t+|my|ပြည်သူပြည်သား}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|nació|f}}\n* Cebuano: {{t|ceb|nasod}}\n* Chavacano: {{t|cbk|nacion}}\n* Cherokee: {{t|chr|ᎠᏰᎵᎯ}}, {{t|chr|ᎠᏰᎵᎤᏙᏢᏒ}}\n* Chichewa: {{t|ny|fuko}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{t+|yue|人民}}, {{t|yue|國民}}\n*: Dungan: {{t|dng|жынмин}}\n*: Eastern Min: {{t|cdo|人民}}, {{t|cdo|國民}}\n*: Gan: {{t|gan|人民}}\n*: Hakka: {{t|hak|人民|tr=ngìn-mìn}}, {{t|hak|國民|tr=koet-mìn}}\n*: Hokkien: {{t+|nan-hbl|人民|tr=jîn-bîn}}, {{t+|nan-hbl|國民|tr=kok-bîn}}\n*: Jin: {{t|cjy|人民}}, {{t|cjy|國民}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|人民}}, {{t+|cmn|國民}}\n*: Northern Min: {{t|mnp|人民}}\n*: Wu: {{t|wuu|人民}}, {{t|wuu|國民}}\n*: Xiang: {{t|hsn|人民}}, {{t|hsn|國民}}\n* Chukchi: {{t|ckt|варат|tr